    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix buffer overflow vulnerability in CLI help command argument handling\n\n### Summary\nThe CLI help command (`com_help`) in `openair2/UTIL/CLI/cli.c` contained a critical buffer overflow vulnerability due to missing range validation on the argument parameter. When a user provided a long command name argument, the function would attempt to print it into a fixed-size buffer without proper bounds checking, potentially leading to memory corruption.\n\nAdditionally, the function was not properly validating command arguments - it would ignore any provided argument and always display help for all commands, rather than filtering to show help for the specific requested command.\n\nThis fix addresses both the security vulnerability and the functional correctness issue.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/UTIL/CLI/cli.c`: \n  - Added proper argument validation in `com_help` function to check if argument matches known commands\n  - Replaced all unsafe `sprintf` calls with `snprintf` for buffer overflow protection\n  - Added bounds checking before printing command documentation strings\n  - Fixed typo in error message (\"commnad\" -> \"command\")\n  - Restructured function logic to properly handle command-specific help requests\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the original issue:\n1. Connect to the OAI CLI interface\n2. Execute `help <very_long_command_string>` where the string exceeds buffer size\n3. Observe potential buffer overflow and memory corruption\n4. Alternatively, execute `help start` and observe that help for all commands is displayed instead of just the 'start' command\n\nAfter applying this fix, the CLI properly validates command arguments and prevents buffer overflows by using safe string operations.\n"
}